epicardium","Fibrous pericardium and visceral pericardium","Fibrous pericardium and endocardium","Myocardium and epicardium","Fibrous pericardium and parietal pericardium"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA pericardial rub is produced by inflammation between the \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal pericardium and epicardium\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as the visceral pericardium). These are the two layers of the serous pericardium that normally slide smoothly against each other during the cardiac cycle. When inflamed, they become rough and produce the characteristic friction rub sound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrous pericardium and visceral pericardium\u003C/strong\u003E are not in direct contact, so inflammation between these layers would not produce a rub. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrous pericardium and endocardium\u003C/strong\u003E are separated by multiple layers and do not interact to produce a rub. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emyocardium and epicardium\u003C/strong\u003E are both part of the heart wall and do not produce a rub when inflamed. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrous pericardium and parietal pericardium\u003C/strong\u003E are adjacent layers but do not move against each other in a way that would produce a rub.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that the pericardium consists of two main layers:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFibrous pericardium (outermost layer)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerous pericardium, which is further divided into:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParietal layer (lines the inner surface of the fibrous pericardium)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVisceral layer (epicardium, adheres to the surface of the heart)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A pericardial rub occurs due to inflammation between the parietal pericardium and visceral pericardium (epicardium).","The pericardium consists of two layers: an outer fibrous pericardium and an inner serous pericardium (which is further divided into parietal and visceral layers)."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Khandaker MH, Espinosa RE, Nishimura RA, Sinak LJ, Hayes SN, Melduni RM, Oh JK. Pericardial disease: diagnosis and management. Mayo Clin Proc. 2010 Jun;85(6):572-93. doi: 10.4065/mcp.2010.0046. PMID: 20511488; PMCID: PMC2878263."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40726"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14399"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40726"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T09:36:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T09:37:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7094"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","n